1. Cloud Fundamentals
    Deployment Models: Public (AWS), Private (on-premise), and Hybrid (mix of both).
    Service Models:
      Cloud service models define what level of control and responsibility you get when using cloud computing. The three core models are IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS (with some modern extensions).

1️⃣ IaaS – Infrastructure as a Service
You manage: OS, runtime, middleware, apps, data
Cloud provider manages: Physical servers, storage, networking, virtualization

What you get
Virtual machines
Storage (block/object)
Networking (VPC, subnets, load balancers)

Examples
AWS: EC2, EBS, S3, VPC
Azure: Virtual Machines
GCP: Compute Engine

When to use
Full control over OS and software
Legacy applications
Custom networking/security requirements

Pros / Cons
✅ Maximum flexibility
❌ More operational overhead
------------
2️⃣ PaaS – Platform as a Service
You manage: Application code, data
Cloud provider manages: OS, runtime, scaling, patching, infra

What you get
Managed runtime environments
Built-in scaling and monitoring
CI/CD friendly platforms

Examples
AWS: Elastic Beanstalk, App Runner
Azure: App Service
GCP: App Engine

Heroku

When to use
Faster development & deployment

You don’t want to manage servers

Pros / Cons
✅ Faster time to market
❌ Less control over environment
------------
3️⃣ SaaS – Software as a Service
You manage: Only usage & configuration
Cloud provider manages: Everything else

What you get
Fully ready-to-use software
Access via browser or API

Examples
Gmail, Google Drive
Salesforce
Slack
Zoom

When to use
No development required

Business productivity tools

Pros / Cons
✅ Zero infrastructure management
❌ Least customization  
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Compute Services (The Brain)
    Amazon EC2: Resizable virtual servers. Know the pricing models: On-Demand (pay-per-use), Reserved 
    (1–3 year commitment for 72% savings), and Spot (spare capacity at high discounts).
    AWS Lambda: Serverless compute that runs code only when triggered by events (e.g., file upload to S3).
    Elastic Beanstalk: An orchestration service that automates deployment, scaling, and load balancing for web apps. 

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Storage & Databases (The Memory)
    Amazon S3: Scalable object storage for files. Offers 99.999999999% durability.
    Amazon EBS: Persistent block storage volumes for EC2 (like a hard drive).
    Databases:
        RDS: Managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle).
        DynamoDB: Fully managed NoSQL database for high-speed, unstructured data.
        Aurora: High-performance, AWS-native relational database compatible with MySQL/PostgreSQL. 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Networking & Content Delivery
    Amazon VPC: Your private, isolated section of the AWS cloud. Key components: Subnets, Route Tables, and Internet Gateways.
    Route 53: A highly available Domain Name System (DNS) for domain registration and traffic routing.
    CloudFront: Content Delivery Network (CDN) that speeds up website delivery using global "Edge Locations".
    Elastic Load Balancing (ELB): Distributes incoming traffic across multiple targets (like EC2 instances) to ensure high availability. 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Security & Management

    AWS IAM: Manage user access. Always follow the Principle of Least Privilege (give only the access needed).
    CloudWatch: Monitoring service for resources and applications; used to set alarms (e.g., if CPU > 80%).
    CloudTrail: Audit logs of every action taken in your AWS account (who did what and when).
    AWS Artifact: Portal for on-demand access to AWS compliance reports (PCI, SOC, ISO)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------
Step 1: The AWS Account (The Hotel Brand)
The Account is the topmost container. It is the legal and financial entity.

    Analogy: This is the "Marriott" or "Hilton" brand level.
    What happens here: This is where you pay the bill and decide who (IAM Users) has the keycards to enter the buildings.
    Expert Rule: Everything you do in AWS happens inside an Account.

Step 2: The Region (The City)
Inside your Account, you must choose a Region. Regions are physical locations around the world.

    Analogy: This is choosing to build in "New York" or "London."
    What fits here: You decide where your data physically sits for speed (latency) or laws (compliance).
    Expert Rule: You can have multiple VPCs in one Region, but a VPC cannot leave its city (Region).

Step 3: The VPC (The Hotel Building)
Inside a Region, you build a VPC (Virtual Private Cloud). This is your private, fenced-in network.

    Analogy: This is the physical Hotel Building. It has a fence around it. No one can get in unless you build a front door (Internet Gateway).
    What fits here: You define the private IP addresses for the whole building (e.g., 10.0.0.0/16).
    Expert Rule: You are the architect of the building. You decide how many floors and rooms it has.

Step 4: The Subnet (The Floor/Room)
Inside your VPC building, you divide the space into Subnets.

    Analogy: These are the Floors of the hotel.
        Public Subnet: The Lobby. Anyone from the street (Internet) can walk in.
        Private Subnet: The Guest Rooms. You need special permission/security to get there; they are not open to the street.
    What fits here: Subnets are tied to a specific Availability Zone (AZ) (think of AZs as separate power grids or wings of the hotel for safety).
    Expert Rule: You put your sensitive stuff (Databases) in the private "rooms" and your website in the "lobby."

Step 5: The Resource (The Guest/Furniture)
Finally, you place the actual Resources inside the Subnets.

    Analogy: This is the Guest (EC2 Instance) or the Safe (Database) inside the room.
    What happens here: The resource gets a specific "Room Number" (Private IP address) from the Subnet it lives in.
    Expert Rule: A resource like an EC2 server must live in one specific Subnet.

The Full "Logic Chain" in One Sentence:

    "My AWS Account owns a Region (City), where I built a VPC (Building), divided into Subnets (Floors), to hold my EC2 Resources (Guests)."

Summary Table for 2025 Mastery
Layer

Technical Name	Who/What lives here?
Level 1	Account	Billing, IAM Users, Security Policies.
Level 2	Region	The physical location (e.g., us-east-1).
Level 3	VPC	Your private IP range and network rules.
Level 4	Subnet	Public or Private access rules (tied to an AZ).
Level 5	Resource	EC2, RDS (Databases), Load Balancers.
Wait, what about S3?
Some resources (like S3 Buckets) are "Global/Regional." They don't live in a VPC or Subnet. Think of S3 as a Storage Warehouse outside the hotel that the hotel guests can send boxes to for safekeeping.
